<HEADLINE>
TWO HOLIDAY MEDICAL STATIONS OPEN IN CHIAYI SCENIC AREAS
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taipei,  Jan.  7 (CNA) 01/07/07  19:07:19 (By Y.L.Kao)
</P>
<P>
The Chiayi county government has set up medical stations at two
of the county's popular tourist spots to offer emergency medical
treatment for visitors during weekends and holiday periods, local
health officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
One station  opened Saturday  at Fenchihu  Scenic Area in
mountainous Chuchi Village, while the other began operations at
Juili Scenic Area in Meishan Village, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
From now on, the officials said, the two new medical stations
will operate weekends and national holidays to serve those who
need treatment for serious injuries or even just first-aid
treatment.
</P>
<P>
The Fenchihu station will operate from 8 p.m. on the eve of every
holiday through 8 p.m. on the last day of the holiday. Juili
station's opening hours will run from 5 p.m. on the eve of the
holiday to 5 p.m. on the last day of the holiday.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, the Cabinet-level Department of
Health has offered a subsidy of NT$12.45 million to help finance
the two medical stations, which will be staffed by medical
professionals from Chiayi Chang Gung Memorial Hospital and Dalin
Tzu Chi General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
Doctors at the station have obtained their Advanced Cardiac Life
Support (ACLS) licenses and nursing practitioners have all passed
the Emergency Trauma Training Course (ETTC), the officials said.
</P>
